uscarinic receptors in airway smooth muscle","Reduces airway inflammation via glucocorticoid receptors"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELong-acting muscarinic antagonists (LAMAs) work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking M3 muscarinic receptors in airway smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E. This prevents acetylcholine-mediated bronchoconstriction, resulting in bronchodilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of phosphodiesterase type 4 enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of roflumilast, which reduces inflammation in airways. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeta-2 agonists like salbutamol \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulate beta-2 adrenergic receptors. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E would worsen bronchospasm; this describes the mechanism of action of beta blockers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduction in airway inflammation via glucocorticoid receptors \u003C/strong\u003Edescribes the mechanism of inhaled corticosteroids (ICS). \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon LAMAs include tiotropium, umeclidinium, and glycopyrronium. They are particularly useful in COPD where cholinergic tone is increased.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Long-acting muscarinic antagonists (LAMAs) work by blocking M3 receptors in airway smooth muscle, leading to bronchodilation.","LAMAs are important maintenance therapy for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).","Common LAMAs include tiotropium, umeclidinium, and glycopyrronium."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), H